    full_explanation: `A Large Language Model (LLM) is an AI system trained on billions of text samples from the internet, books, and other sources. During training, the model learns statistical patterns in language — which words and phrases tend to follow others — and uses those patterns to generate coherent text.\n\nThe "large" in LLM refers to the number of parameters (settings) the model has, typically billions. More parameters generally means the model can capture more complex patterns and produce more capable output.\n\nWhen you give an LLM a prompt, it predicts the most likely continuation of that text based on everything it learned during training. This simple mechanism produces responses that can seem remarkably intelligent, nuanced, or creative.\n\nPopular LLMs include GPT-4o (OpenAI), Claude 3.5 Sonnet (Anthropic), Gemini 1.5 Pro (Google), and Llama 3.1 (Meta).`,
