    title: 'RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)',
    slug: 'rag',
    simple_definition: 'A technique that lets AI models answer questions using your specific documents or data, not just their training data.',
    full_explanation: `Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a way to make AI models more accurate and specific by giving them access to your own knowledge base at query time.\n\nHere's how it works: when you ask a question, the system first searches your document collection for the most relevant passages (retrieval), then injects those passages into the AI's context along with your question (augmentation), and the AI generates an answer based on what it retrieved (generation).\n\nThis solves two major limitations of language models: knowledge cutoffs (models don't know about documents written after their training ended) and hallucination on specific facts (models may make up details they weren't trained on).\n\nRAG requires a vector database to store embedded representations of your documents, and an embedding model to convert text into searchable vectors. Common implementations use Supabase pgvector, Pinecone, or Chroma as the vector store.`,
