    simple_definition: 'The maximum amount of text an AI model can process at once — everything it "sees" when generating a response.',
    full_explanation: `The context window is the total amount of text (measured in tokens) that a language model can process in a single request — including your conversation history, any documents you've uploaded, the system prompt, and the model's previous responses.\n\nThink of it as the model's working memory. Everything inside the context window the model "knows about" when generating its response. Anything outside the window, the model has no access to.\n\nContext windows vary significantly across models: GPT-4o mini has 128K tokens (~96K words), Claude 3.5 Sonnet has 200K tokens (~150K words), and Gemini 1.5 Pro has 1 million tokens (~750K words — enough for an entire novel plus the complete works of Shakespeare).\n\nImportant distinction: a model having a long context window doesn't mean it uses it equally well throughout. Some models "forget" information from early in the context when the window is nearly full. Claude and Gemini are generally better at using long contexts than earlier models.`,
