    title: 'Hallucination',
    slug: 'hallucination',
    simple_definition: 'When an AI model generates false or made-up information that sounds confident and plausible.',
    full_explanation: `Hallucination is when a language model generates text that is factually incorrect, fabricated, or nonsensical — but stated with the same confidence as accurate information. The model doesn't know it's wrong; it's generating text that statistically "fits" the conversation, whether or not it's true.\n\nHallucinations can be subtle (a slightly wrong date, a made-up statistic) or egregious (a completely fictional event described as fact, a real person attributed a quote they never said, a non-existent research paper with a plausible-sounding title).\n\nWhy it happens: language models predict the next token based on patterns, not a lookup from a database of facts. When asked about something obscure or outside their training data, they generate plausible-sounding text rather than saying "I don't know."\n\nMitigation strategies: RAG (ground the model in verified documents), citations required (ask the model to cite sources — it will hallucinate less when forced to attribute), verification (always check important facts from an independent source), and lower temperature (more conservative, less creative outputs).`,
