    simple_definition: 'Mathematical representations of text as numbers that capture semantic meaning, enabling AI to find similar content.',
    full_explanation: `Embeddings are a way of representing text, images, or other content as lists of numbers (vectors) that capture semantic meaning. Two pieces of text with similar meaning will have similar vectors, even if they use different words.\n\nFor example, "the dog ran fast" and "the canine moved quickly" would produce similar embedding vectors, while "the dog ran fast" and "quarterly earnings report" would produce very different vectors.\n\nEmbeddings are fundamental to semantic search and RAG systems: when you search for "best way to reduce customer churn," an embedding-based search finds documents about "improving customer retention" and "reducing subscription cancellations" — semantically similar content that keyword search would miss.\n\nCreating embeddings requires an embedding model (separate from a language model). OpenAI's text-embedding-3-small and text-embedding-3-large are popular choices. Google and Cohere also offer embedding models.\n\nOnce embedded, text is stored in a vector database (like Supabase pgvector, Pinecone, or Chroma) and searched using vector similarity (cosine similarity or dot product).`,
