    simple_definition: 'A database optimized for storing and searching embeddings (vector representations of text or images).',
    full_explanation: `A vector database is a specialized database designed to store, index, and search high-dimensional vectors (embeddings). Unlike a traditional database that searches by exact match or range queries, a vector database searches by similarity — finding vectors that are mathematically close to a query vector.\n\nThe core operation is approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) search: given a query embedding, find the k most similar stored embeddings. This enables semantic search across millions of documents in milliseconds.\n\nPopular vector databases: Pinecone (cloud-native, fully managed), Weaviate (open source with cloud option), Qdrant (open source, high performance), Chroma (simple, good for development), and Supabase pgvector (Postgres extension, good if you're already using Postgres).\n\nA typical RAG workflow: chunk documents → embed each chunk → store embeddings in vector DB → at query time, embed the query → search vector DB for similar chunks → pass chunks as context to LLM → generate grounded answer.`,
