    simple_definition: 'A feature that lets AI models call external functions or APIs with structured parameters during a conversation.',
    full_explanation: `Function calling (also called tool use) is a feature where a language model can detect when it needs external data or capabilities, and request that a specific function be called with specific parameters — rather than generating a text response.\n\nFor example: if a user asks "What is the weather in Dubai right now?", the model can't answer from training data (it doesn't have real-time weather). With function calling enabled, it instead outputs a structured request: call the get_weather function with location="Dubai". Your code executes that function, gets the result, and passes it back to the model, which then answers the original question.\n\nFunction calling is what makes AI agents possible: the model reasons about which tools to use, calls them in sequence, and uses the results to accomplish complex goals.\n\nAll major models support function calling: GPT-4o (OpenAI), Claude 3.5 Sonnet (Anthropic), Gemini 1.5 Pro (Google). The model generates a JSON object with the function name and parameters, which you parse and execute.`,
