    full_explanation: `Fine-tuning is the process of taking a pre-trained language model and continuing to train it on a smaller, task-specific dataset. The result is a model that retains the base model's general capabilities but performs better on your specific use case.\n\nFor example: you might fine-tune GPT-4o mini on 500 examples of your company's customer support responses, teaching it to match your brand voice, use your product-specific terminology, and follow your support policies — things that would require a very long system prompt to achieve with prompt engineering alone.\n\nFine-tuning is expensive (you need quality training data and compute) and requires ongoing maintenance as your product changes. It's typically considered when prompt engineering alone can't achieve required quality or consistency.\n\nMore common alternatives: RAG (give the model your documents at query time) for knowledge tasks, and prompt engineering with few-shot examples for style/format tasks. Fine-tuning is the right choice when you need consistent style, specialized vocabulary, or behavior that can't be achieved with prompts.`,
