    title: 'Temperature',
    slug: 'temperature',
    simple_definition: 'A setting that controls how creative vs. predictable an AI model\'s responses are. Higher = more random; lower = more focused.',
    full_explanation: `Temperature is a parameter that controls the randomness of a language model's output. It affects how the model samples from the probability distribution of possible next tokens.\n\nAt temperature 0, the model always picks the most probable next token — resulting in deterministic, predictable output. The same prompt will produce the same response every time. This is good for precise tasks like data extraction, classification, or code generation where you want consistent results.\n\nAt temperature 1 (the typical default), the model samples according to the natural probability distribution — introducing some variation. Different runs of the same prompt will produce somewhat different responses.\n\nAt temperature 2 (maximum in most APIs), the model samples from a much flatter distribution — very creative but also more likely to produce incoherent or off-topic output.\n\nPractical guidance: use 0 or 0.1 for structured data extraction, classification, and code. Use 0.7-1.0 for creative writing, brainstorming, and conversation. Rarely go above 1.2.`,
    example: 'Ask GPT-4o "What is the capital of France?" at temperature 0 → always "Paris." At temperature 1.5 → might say "Paris" or might produce something unexpected. For a code debugging task, use temperature 0. For writing 10 different social media captions, use temperature 1.',
    why_it_matters: 'Temperature is the most commonly tuned parameter in AI APIs. Getting it right improves output quality for your specific use case.',
