    title: 'Multimodal AI',
    slug: 'multimodal-ai',
    simple_definition: 'AI that can process and generate multiple types of content — text, images, audio, and video — not just text.',
    full_explanation: `Multimodal AI refers to AI systems that can understand and generate multiple types of media — text, images, audio, video, or combinations of them — rather than being limited to a single modality like text.\n\nEarly AI models were unimodal: a language model could only process text, an image classifier could only classify images. Modern multimodal models can process several types of input simultaneously and generate different types of output.\n\nExamples of multimodal capabilities: GPT-4o accepts text and images as input, generates text and audio; Gemini 1.5 Pro accepts text, images, audio, and video; DALL-E 3 accepts text and generates images; Whisper accepts audio and generates text transcription.\n\nNative multimodality (processing all modes in one model) is different from pipeline-based multimodality (using separate models for each mode and chaining them together). GPT-4o is natively multimodal, meaning the same model processes text and vision — this enables more coherent cross-modal reasoning.`,
    example: 'A natively multimodal model can look at a chart image and a table of data simultaneously and explain how they relate. A non-multimodal pipeline would need separate models for image understanding and text analysis, with no direct connection.',
