    title: 'Zero-shot',
    slug: 'zero-shot',
    simple_definition: 'Asking an AI model to perform a task without giving it any examples — relying entirely on its training.',
    full_explanation: `Zero-shot prompting means giving a language model a task instruction without providing any examples of what good output looks like. The model relies entirely on its training to understand and complete the task.\n\nMost casual AI use is zero-shot: "Write an email declining this meeting" or "Summarize this article." You describe what you want, and the model does it based on what it learned from training data.\n\nZero-shot works well for common, well-defined tasks where the model has seen many examples during training. It's faster (shorter prompts) and often good enough for general tasks.\n\nWhen zero-shot fails — when you need specific output format, terminology, or style — the alternative is few-shot prompting: providing 2-5 examples of the desired input-output pairs directly in your prompt. Few-shot is more reliable for specialized or unusual task formats.`,
    example: 'Zero-shot: "Classify this customer email as: complaint, question, or praise." → The model classifies it without seeing any example classifications. Few-shot: you first show 3 example emails with their correct labels, then ask the model to classify a new one.',
    why_it_matters: 'Understanding the difference between zero-shot and few-shot helps you choose the right prompting strategy for your task — simple descriptions vs. providing examples.',
    where_its_used: 'Any AI prompt is either zero-shot (no examples given) or few-shot (examples provided). The distinction matters for prompt design.',
