    simple_definition: 'Creating an AI version of a specific person\'s voice that can read any text in their voice.',
    full_explanation: `Voice cloning is the process of creating an AI model of a specific person's voice using audio samples, which can then generate speech in that voice from any text input — without that person present.\n\nThe technology requires: a voice sample (typically 60 seconds to 30 minutes of clean audio), a voice cloning model (ElevenLabs Instant Clone or Professional Clone, Eleven v3), and a text-to-speech synthesis step that applies the cloned voice to new text.\n\nQuality varies with sample length: Instant Voice Cloning (ElevenLabs) works from 60 seconds of audio and produces good quality. Professional Voice Cloning uses a 30-minute training session recorded in controlled conditions and produces near-perfect results — indistinguishable from the original voice to most listeners.\n\nEthics and consent: voice cloning requires explicit consent from the person whose voice is being cloned. ElevenLabs requires a voice consent statement recorded by the person before cloning their voice. Using voice cloning without consent is legally problematic and ethically wrong.\n\nApplications: content creators who want to produce audio without recording sessions, multilingual content where the speaker\'s voice is maintained across languages, and accessibility tools.`,
