    full_explanation: `Top-P (also called nucleus sampling) is a sampling parameter that complements temperature in controlling language model output. While temperature adjusts how randomly tokens are selected, Top-P limits which tokens are considered in the first place.\n\nAt Top-P = 0.9, the model only samples from the smallest set of tokens whose combined probability sums to 90%. This excludes very unlikely tokens from consideration, preventing wildly off-topic outputs.\n\nAt Top-P = 1.0 (the default in most APIs), all tokens are considered regardless of probability — the model can pick any token, including very unlikely ones.\n\nLower Top-P (0.1 - 0.5) makes outputs more focused and predictable. Higher Top-P (0.9-1.0) allows more diverse and creative outputs. Most practitioners find temperature is a more intuitive parameter to adjust; Top-P is often left at its default.\n\nSome model APIs let you adjust both; others simplify by using only temperature or recommending you adjust one but not both simultaneously.`,
